UML:TaggedValue.value: The functional requirements also appear in the Use Cases chapter linked to the corresponding Use Case(s). In this chapter they are presented with their status.
The operator is responsible for the management of the assets.
The SmartClient provides the user interface for the operator to the Dynamic Rating System.
This use case describes the interaction from the operator with the overview information provided by the KEMA Dynamic Rating System.
This use case shows the information about an asset of the 'cable' type.
This use case shows the information about an asset of the 'transformer' type.
This use case shows the information about an asset of the 'line' type.
At all time, the operator sees the aggragated alarm status on screen.
As soon as an alarm is raised, the operator receives a notification per e-mail.
The operator receives an indication of the aggragated alarm status per managed asset,
The alarm overview shows the operator the active warnings and alarms and all alarms and warnings that have not been acknowledged.
As soon as an alarm is raised, the operator receives a notification on screen.

This use case imports data from files. This can be historic data or actual data.
Constraints 1. Correct behavior is only guaranteed when for a managed asset only one history input data file from the input data location that matches the input data filename pattern is imported.
2. To prevent the DRS to use the specified values the actual data must be delivered without delay at the specified sample time.
3. Input data older than already processed data (processed with either measured or specified values) will be ignored.
The Dynamic Rating System can only be used when a valid license is available.
The license defines the maximum number of assets that can be managed.
The license file is a XML file that must be written according to the schema 'License.xsd'.
The SmartClient application will react within 8 seconds to new data, alarms and emergencies.
The system must support up to 5 assets to manage simultaneously
All imported floating point numbers will be written and read according to the regional settings of the system.
For a cable asset each line with data consists of the following fields seperated by TABs: = current = ambient temperature

For a line asset each line with data consists of the following fields seperated by TABs: = datasetnumber = current = ground temperature (must be present but will be ignored) = Air temperature = Solar Radiation = Wind speed = Wind Angle
The header of the historical data input file consist of 1 line with the name of the asset to be imported. Additional header lines will be ignored.
The historical data file contains a header and one or more lines with data.
The actual data must be written in a XML file which must be placed in the input data location of the Dynamic Rating System.

The following substitution parameters are allowed in an email template: * {Asset} the name of the asset which this e-mail relates to. * {Timestamp}: holds the date and time when the alarm was raised. The names are case sensitive.

The historical data is written to a text file with a name like '<assettype>_invoer.txt', '<assettype>_invoer2.txt', '<assettype>_invoer3.txt' and must be placed in the incoming data directory of the Dynamic Rating System. Where <assetype> is one of 'lijn', 'kabel' or 'trafo'.
The name and location of the forecasted meteorological data input file is configurable.
The forecasted meteorological data is written to a XML file which must be placed in the input data location of the Dynamic Rating System.
The actual data XML file shall be written according to the schema 'EmsInput.xsd'.
The forecasted meteorological data XML file shall be written according to the schema 'ForecastedMeteo.xsd'.
The name of the actual data input file is configurable.
The substitution parameters in an email template must be placed between curly-brackets { and }.
For a cable asset each line with data consists of the following fields seperated by TABs: = current = ground temperature

The status of an alarm of a monitored value of an asset. Possible values are: * Normal - If not in a Warning or Alarm state * Warning - If the value exceeds has exceeded the warning threshold but is below the alarm threshold * Alarm - If the value has exceed the alarm threshold * 'Missing data' - If no meqasured values have been received for a configurable time.

If all of the alarm statuses (part of the aggregated alarm status) have the value Normal, the aggregated alarm status indication shall be a blue asset alarm bar for that asset
An alarm shall be presented in the color red.
If one or more of the alarm statuses (part of the aggregated alarm status) have the value alarm, the aggregated alarm status indication shall be a red asset alarm bar for the asset.
The operator shall be able to acknowledge the alarms in the unsolicited alarm notification.
The unsolicited notification shall show all unacknowledged alarms and warnings.
It shall be possible to sort the information in the alarm overview.
The e-mail shall contain the e-mail address configurable parameters: * From address * To address * CC address
The operator shall get an indication that no alarms and no warnings are present for the managed assets.
For each alarm in the unsolicited alarm notification, the following information is shown: * Alarm state (active, not active) * Asset name * Alarm status (warning, alarm).
Upon acknowledgement of a (pre-)alarm with alarm status 'inactive', the (pre-)alarm shall be removed from the alarm overview.

When a warning or alarm with state 'inactive' is acknowledged, the warning or alarm shall be removed from the alarm overview.

The system shall send an e-mail to the e-mail server as soon as one of the following situations occurs: - Missing data alarm - Warning on current - Alarm on current - Warning on temperature - Alarm on temperature
The e-mail subject shall contain a short description of the warning or alarm and the asset name.

If one or more of the alarm statuses (part of the aggregated alarm status) have the value 'Warning' and no alarm status (part of the aggregated alarm status) with the value Alarm is present, the aggregated alarm status indication shall be a orange asset alarm bar for the asset.
The unsolicited alarm notification window shall always be on top of all other windows (except for Windows Task Manager).
The operator shall get an indication of the aggregated alarm status for each asset at all times.

As soon as all alarms are acknowledged, the unsolicited alarm notification disappears.
Email will be sent using the SMTP protocol using a configurable host address and port number.
The e-mail body for an alarm or warning is generated from an email template in which the asset name and the timestamp can be inserted at runtime.
An e-mail shall be sent when an alarm status makes a transition: * From Normal to Warning * From Normal to Alarm * From Warning to Alarm * From Alarm to Warning.
The asset name shall be shown as soon as a warning or alarm becomes active.
For each managed asset the operator shall get an indication of the aggregated alarm status of that asset on an asset alarm bar.
The operator shall receive an unsolicited notification as soon as an alarm is raised.
Unacknowledged active alarms or warnings are displayed bold in the alarm overview.
The asset name shall be removed as soon as the warnings and alarms have become inactive.
It shall be possible to sort the information in the unsolicited alarm notification.
The asset names shall be displayed in the color 'red'.
A warning or alarm with alarm state 'inactive' shall be presented in the color grey.

The subject for each e-mail template are defined in translations.xml: * SubjectAlarmMissingData * SubjectAlarmTemperature * SubjectAlarmCurrent * SubjectAlarmWarningCurrent * SubjectAlarmWarningTemperature
In the alarm overview the operator is presented an overview of all active warnings and alarms and of all unacknowledged inactive warnings and alarms.

For each warning or alarm, the following information shall be available: * Alarm acknowledgement status (acknowledged, unacknowledged) * Alarm state (active, not active) * Asset name * Alarm status (warning, alarm).

For the selected asset a graphical presentation is shown when the tab 'Dynamic Result Model' is selected.
For a Line asset with a second dataset defined in addition is shown: = Air temperature (corrected) = Core temperature (corrected)

The operator can select the resolution of the horizontal time axis. He has the fo)llowuing choices: = last 4 hours = last 8 hours = last 12 hours = last 16 hours = last day = last 2 days = last 3 days = last week = last 2 weeks = last mont = last 2 months = all data (limited to a maximum of 1 year)
For a Line asset the following information is shown: = Current in A = Air temperature = Core temperature

When the user selects a point on the graph on tab page "Emergency situations", the selected values (time interval and current) should be displayed in the corresponding box on tab page "Operational Overview"
Historical data will be imported starting at the last known imported timestamp for the asset / dataset + the configured sample time.
The first data row in the history input data file is imported and assigned a data timestamp equal to the data input start timestamp.
The Dynamic Rating System checks periodically whether an input data file is available at the input data location.
If there was no previous import in the history and if no data has been processed then historical data importing will start at the configured StartValue timestamp + the configured sampletime
If no filename matches the input data filename pattern, processing will use specified values.
After the input data file has been imported the input data file is removed from the input data location.
The Dynaminc Rating System can import forecasts for the meteorological conditions.
If no data has been imported for that asset / dataset, but there was processed data then historical data importing will start at the last processed timestamp + the configured sampletime.
If more than 1 inputfile is available it is not defined which file will be processed first.

When using historical data and no datasetnumber is specified for a line asset the import process processing stop processing this datapoint and will continue with the next line in the historical data file. An error will be logged.
The actual data file contains exactly 1 data sample.
Consecutive (2 and more) data rows in the history input data file are imported and assigned a data time stamp: data input start time + ((data row number -1) * data input sample time).
The Dynamic Rating System can be configured to import historical data or actual data, but not both at the same time.
When using actual data and no datasetnumber is specified for a line asset the import process will stop processing this file and logs an error.
The location of the input data location is configurable .
When using actual data the timestamp in that datafile is used.
The name of the files in the input data location are matched against the input data filename pattern.
If a filename matches the input data filename pattern, the file is imported and the data is stored for later processing.
If 2 datasets are defined for a Line asset the values of dataset 1 will not be corrected by the values of dataset 2.
Line asset calculated values: = Core temperature (in degrees Celsius)
For each managed transformer asset the DRS will monitor the current and the hotspot temperature.
Cable start values: Timestamp Current Ground temperature
When a monitored value is below or equal to the Warning threshold the alarm status is 'Normal'
If 2 datasets are defined for a Line asset the values in the imported data for dataset 1 are the actual measured current and the forecasted meteo data.
A 'Missing data alarm' is raised when no measured values for a managed asset have been received during a configured time.
The measured values of a Line asset will always refer to the dataset for which the values are vaild.

An 'Warning' is raised when the alarm status of a monitored value changes from 'Normal' to 'Warning'.
If 2 datasets are defined for a Line asset the values in the imported data for dataset 2 are the actual measured current and the actual meteo data.
For Line assets alarms will always be based only on the data from dataset 1.
Line asset measured values: = DatasetNumber (1 or 2) = Current (in ampere) = Air temperature (in degrees Celsius) = Solar radiation (in W /m2) = Wind speed (in m/s) = Wind angle (in degrees)

Imported data with a non configured datasetnumber will be ignored.
If only 1 dataset is used for a Line asset the values in the imported data are the actual measured values.
If no data is received for a Line asset for dataset 1 the configured specified meteorological data and the configured specified current will be used.
Line start values: Timestamp N * dataset { Current SolarRadiation AirTemperature WindSpeed WindDirection }
Trafo asset specified values: Forecasted currents (in ampere) for one day specified per hour of a day and forecasted ambient (=air) temperatures (in degrees Celsius) per hour of a day.
Line asset specified values: Forecasted currents (in ampere) for one day specified per hour of a day and forecasted ambient temperatures (in degrees Celsius) per hour of a day.
Line parameters: ResistanceDC TempCoefficientCM SkinEffectTI SkinEffectTD AbsorbtivityOfCS Epsilon DiameterOuter DiameterWire MassSpecTI MassSpecTD MaxTemperature ThermalResistance Height Orientation
Dataset 1 and dataset 2 will have the same sample rate
When a monitored value is below or equal to the Alarm threshold but exceeds the Warning threshold the alarm status is 'Warning'
Cable asset specified values: Forecasted currents (in ampere) for one day specified per hour of a day and forecasted ground temperatures (in degrees Celsius) per month of a year.
Cable asset calculated values: = Conductor temperature (in degrees Celsius) = Sheath temperature (in degrees Celsius) = Jacket temperature (in degrees Celsius)
